maze_dataset

maze-dataset

This package provides utilities for generation, filtering, solving, visualizing, and processing of mazes for training ML systems. Primarily built for the maze-transformer interpretability project. You can find our paper on it here: http://arxiv.org/abs/2309.10498

This package includes a variety of maze generation algorithms, including randomized depth first search, Wilson's algorithm for uniform spanning trees, and percolation. Datasets can be filtered to select mazes of a certain length or complexity, remove duplicates, and satisfy custom properties. A variety of output formats for visualization and training ML models are provided.

Installation

This package is available on PyPI, and can be installed via

pip install maze-dataset

Docs

The full hosted documentation is available at https://understanding-search.github.io/maze-dataset/.

Additionally:

  • our notebooks serve as a good starting point for understanding the package:
    • the notebooks page in the docs has links to the rendered notebooks
    • the notebooks folder has the source notebooks
  • combined, single page docs are available as:
    • plain text
    • html
    • github markdown
    • pandoc markdown
  • test coverage reports are available on the coverage page or the coverage/ folder
  • generation benchmark results are available on the benchmarks page or the benchmarks/ folder

Usage

Creating a dataset

To create a MazeDataset, which inherits from torch.utils.data.Dataset, you first create a MazeDatasetConfig:

from maze_dataset import MazeDataset, MazeDatasetConfig
from maze_dataset.generation import LatticeMazeGenerators
cfg: MazeDatasetConfig = MazeDatasetConfig(
    name="test", # name is only for you to keep track of things
    grid_n=5, # number of rows/columns in the lattice
    n_mazes=4, # number of mazes to generate
    maze_ctor=LatticeMazeGenerators.gen_dfs, # algorithm to generate the maze
    maze_ctor_kwargs=dict(do_forks=False), # additional parameters to pass to the maze generation algorithm
)

and then pass this config to the MazeDataset.from_config method:

dataset: MazeDataset = MazeDataset.from_config(cfg)

This method can search for whether a dataset with matching config hash already exists on your filesystem in the expected location, and load it if so. It can also generate a dataset on the fly if needed.

Conversions to useful formats

The elements of the dataset are SolvedMaze objects:

>>> m = dataset[0]
>>> type(m)
SolvedMaze

Which can be converted to a variety of formats:

# visual representation as ascii art
m.as_ascii() 
# RGB image, optionally without solution or endpoints, suitable for CNNs
m.as_pixels() 
# text format for autoreregressive transformers
from maze_dataset.tokenization import MazeTokenizerModular, TokenizationMode
m.as_tokens(maze_tokenizer=MazeTokenizerModular(
    tokenization_mode=TokenizationMode.AOTP_UT_rasterized, max_grid_size=100,
))
# advanced visualization with many features
from maze_dataset.plotting import MazePlot
MazePlot(maze).plot()

Development

This project uses Poetry for development. To install with dev requirements, run

poetry install --with dev

A makefile is included to simplify common development tasks:

  • make help will print all available commands
  • all tests via make test
    • unit tests via make unit
    • notebook tests via make test_notebooks
  • formatter (black, pycln, and isort) via make format
    • formatter in check-only mode via make check-format

class SolvedMaze(maze_dataset.TargetedLatticeMaze):

1110@serializable_dataclass(frozen=True, kw_only=True)
1111class SolvedMaze(TargetedLatticeMaze):
1112    """Stores a maze and a solution"""
1113
1114    solution: CoordArray
1115
1116    def __init__(
1117        self,
1118        connection_list: ConnectionList,
1119        solution: CoordArray,
1120        generation_meta: dict | None = None,
1121        start_pos: Coord | None = None,
1122        end_pos: Coord | None = None,
1123        allow_invalid: bool = False,
1124    ) -> None:
1125        # figure out the solution
1126        solution_valid: bool = False
1127        if solution is not None:
1128            solution = np.array(solution)
1129            # note that a path length of 1 here is valid, since the start and end pos could be the same
1130            if (solution.shape[0] > 0) and (solution.shape[1] == 2):
1131                solution_valid = True
1132
1133        if not solution_valid and not allow_invalid:
1134            raise ValueError(
1135                f"invalid solution: {solution.shape = } {solution = } {solution_valid = } {allow_invalid = }",
1136                f"{connection_list = }",
1137            )
1138
1139        # init the TargetedLatticeMaze
1140        super().__init__(
1141            connection_list=connection_list,
1142            generation_meta=generation_meta,
1143            start_pos=np.array(solution[0]) if solution_valid else None,
1144            end_pos=np.array(solution[-1]) if solution_valid else None,
1145        )
1146
1147        self.__dict__["solution"] = solution
1148
1149        # adjust the endpoints
1150        if not allow_invalid:
1151            if start_pos is not None:
1152                assert np.array_equal(
1153                    np.array(start_pos), self.start_pos
1154                ), f"when trying to create a SolvedMaze, the given start_pos does not match the one in the solution: given={start_pos}, solution={self.start_pos}"
1155            if end_pos is not None:
1156                assert np.array_equal(
1157                    np.array(end_pos), self.end_pos
1158                ), f"when trying to create a SolvedMaze, the given end_pos does not match the one in the solution: given={end_pos}, solution={self.end_pos}"
1159            # TODO: assert the path does not backtrack, walk through walls, etc?
1160
1161    def __hash__(self) -> int:
1162        return hash((self.connection_list.tobytes(), self.solution.tobytes()))
1163
1164    def _get_solution_tokens(self) -> list[str | CoordTup]:
1165        return [
1166            SPECIAL_TOKENS.PATH_START,
1167            *[tuple(c) for c in self.solution],
1168            SPECIAL_TOKENS.PATH_END,
1169        ]
1170
1171    def get_solution_tokens(self) -> list[str | CoordTup]:
1172        warnings.warn(
1173            "`LatticeMaze.get_solution_tokens` is deprecated.",
1174            TokenizerDeprecationWarning,
1175        )
1176        return self._get_solution_tokens()
1177
1178    # for backwards compatibility
1179    @property
1180    def maze(self) -> LatticeMaze:
1181        warnings.warn(
1182            "`maze` is deprecated, SolvedMaze now inherits from LatticeMaze.",
1183            DeprecationWarning,
1184        )
1185        return LatticeMaze(connection_list=self.connection_list)
1186
1187    @classmethod
1188    def from_lattice_maze(
1189        cls, lattice_maze: LatticeMaze, solution: list[CoordTup]
1190    ) -> "SolvedMaze":
1191        return cls(
1192            connection_list=lattice_maze.connection_list,
1193            solution=solution,
1194            generation_meta=lattice_maze.generation_meta,
1195        )
1196
1197    @classmethod
1198    def from_targeted_lattice_maze(
1199        cls,
1200        targeted_lattice_maze: TargetedLatticeMaze,
1201        solution: list[CoordTup] | None = None,
1202    ) -> "SolvedMaze":
1203        """solves the given targeted lattice maze and returns a SolvedMaze"""
1204        if solution is None:
1205            solution = targeted_lattice_maze.find_shortest_path(
1206                targeted_lattice_maze.start_pos,
1207                targeted_lattice_maze.end_pos,
1208            )
1209        return cls(
1210            connection_list=targeted_lattice_maze.connection_list,
1211            solution=np.array(solution),
1212            generation_meta=targeted_lattice_maze.generation_meta,
1213        )
1214
1215    def get_solution_forking_points(
1216        self,
1217        always_include_endpoints: bool = False,
1218    ) -> tuple[list[int], CoordArray]:
1219        """coordinates and their indicies from the solution where a fork is present
1220
1221        - if the start point is not a dead end, this counts as a fork
1222        - if the end point is not a dead end, this counts as a fork
1223        """
1224        output_idxs: list[int] = list()
1225        output_coords: list[CoordTup] = list()
1226
1227        for idx, coord in enumerate(self.solution):
1228            # more than one choice for first coord, or more than 2 for any other
1229            # since the previous coord doesn't count as a choice
1230            is_endpoint: bool = idx == 0 or idx == self.solution.shape[0] - 1
1231            theshold: int = 1 if is_endpoint else 2
1232            if self.get_coord_neighbors(coord).shape[0] > theshold or (
1233                is_endpoint and always_include_endpoints
1234            ):
1235                output_idxs.append(idx)
1236                output_coords.append(coord)
1237
1238        return output_idxs, np.array(output_coords)
1239
1240    def get_solution_path_following_points(self) -> tuple[list[int], CoordArray]:
1241        """coordinates from the solution where there is only a single (non-backtracking) point to move to
1242
1243        returns the complement of `get_solution_forking_points` from the path"""
1244        forks_idxs, _ = self.get_solution_forking_points()
1245        return (
1246            np.delete(np.arange(self.solution.shape[0]), forks_idxs, axis=0),
1247            np.delete(self.solution, forks_idxs, axis=0),
1248        )

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

@staticmethod
def maze_ctor( grid_shape: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'], lattice_dim: int = 2, accessible_cells: int | float | None = None, max_tree_depth: int | float | None = None, do_forks: bool = True, randomized_stack: bool = False, start_coord: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'] | None = None) -> LatticeMaze:
View on GitHub 
 55    @staticmethod
 56    def gen_dfs(
 57        grid_shape: Coord,
 58        lattice_dim: int = 2,
 59        accessible_cells: int | float | None = None,
 60        max_tree_depth: int | float | None = None,
 61        do_forks: bool = True,
 62        randomized_stack: bool = False,
 63        start_coord: Coord | None = None,
 64    ) -> LatticeMaze:
 65        """generate a lattice maze using depth first search, iterative
 66
 67        # Arguments
 68        - `grid_shape: Coord`: the shape of the grid
 69        - `lattice_dim: int`: the dimension of the lattice
 70          (default: `2`)
 71        - `accessible_cells: int | float |None`: the number of accessible cells in the maze. If `None`, defaults to the total number of cells in the grid. if a float, asserts it is <= 1 and treats it as a proportion of **total cells**
 72            (default: `None`)
 73        - `max_tree_depth: int | float | None`: the maximum depth of the tree. If `None`, defaults to `2 * accessible_cells`. if a float, asserts it is <= 1 and treats it as a proportion of the **sum of the grid shape**
 74            (default: `None`)
 75        - `do_forks: bool`: whether to allow forks in the maze. If `False`, the maze will be have no forks and will be a simple hallway.
 76        - `start_coord: Coord | None`: the starting coordinate of the generation algorithm. If `None`, defaults to a random coordinate.
 77
 78        # algorithm
 79        1. Choose the initial cell, mark it as visited and push it to the stack
 80        2. While the stack is not empty
 81                1. Pop a cell from the stack and make it a current cell
 82                2. If the current cell has any neighbours which have not been visited
 83                        1. Push the current cell to the stack
 84                        2. Choose one of the unvisited neighbours
 85                        3. Remove the wall between the current cell and the chosen cell
 86                        4. Mark the chosen cell as visited and push it to the stack
 87        """
 88
 89        # Default values if no constraints have been passed
 90        grid_shape: Coord = np.array(grid_shape)
 91        n_total_cells: int = int(np.prod(grid_shape))
 92
 93        n_accessible_cells: int
 94        if accessible_cells is None:
 95            n_accessible_cells = n_total_cells
 96        elif isinstance(accessible_cells, float):
 97            assert (
 98                accessible_cells <= 1
 99            ), f"accessible_cells must be an int (count) or a float in the range [0, 1] (proportion), got {accessible_cells}"
100
101            n_accessible_cells = int(accessible_cells * n_total_cells)
102        else:
103            assert isinstance(accessible_cells, int)
104            n_accessible_cells = accessible_cells
105
106        if max_tree_depth is None:
107            max_tree_depth = (
108                2 * n_total_cells
109            )  # We define max tree depth counting from the start coord in two directions. Therefore we divide by two in the if clause for neighboring sites later and multiply by two here.
110        elif isinstance(max_tree_depth, float):
111            assert (
112                max_tree_depth <= 1
113            ), f"max_tree_depth must be an int (count) or a float in the range [0, 1] (proportion), got {max_tree_depth}"
114
115            max_tree_depth = int(max_tree_depth * np.sum(grid_shape))
116
117        # choose a random start coord
118        start_coord = _random_start_coord(grid_shape, start_coord)
119
120        # initialize the maze with no connections
121        connection_list: ConnectionList = np.zeros(
122            (lattice_dim, grid_shape[0], grid_shape[1]), dtype=np.bool_
123        )
124
125        # initialize the stack with the target coord
126        visited_cells: set[tuple[int, int]] = set()
127        visited_cells.add(tuple(start_coord))  # this wasnt a bug after all lol
128        stack: list[Coord] = [start_coord]
129
130        # initialize tree_depth_counter
131        current_tree_depth: int = 1
132
133        # loop until the stack is empty or n_connected_cells is reached
134        while stack and (len(visited_cells) < n_accessible_cells):
135            # get the current coord from the stack
136            current_coord: Coord
137            if randomized_stack:
138                current_coord = stack.pop(random.randint(0, len(stack) - 1))
139            else:
140                current_coord = stack.pop()
141
142            # filter neighbors by being within grid bounds and being unvisited
143            unvisited_neighbors_deltas: list[tuple[Coord, Coord]] = [
144                (neighbor, delta)
145                for neighbor, delta in zip(
146                    current_coord + NEIGHBORS_MASK, NEIGHBORS_MASK
147                )
148                if (
149                    (tuple(neighbor) not in visited_cells)
150                    and (0 <= neighbor[0] < grid_shape[0])
151                    and (0 <= neighbor[1] < grid_shape[1])
152                )
153            ]
154
155            # don't continue if max_tree_depth/2 is already reached (divide by 2 because we can branch to multiple directions)
156            if unvisited_neighbors_deltas and (
157                current_tree_depth <= max_tree_depth / 2
158            ):
159                # if we want a maze without forks, simply don't add the current coord back to the stack
160                if do_forks and (len(unvisited_neighbors_deltas) > 1):
161                    stack.append(current_coord)
162
163                # choose one of the unvisited neighbors
164                chosen_neighbor, delta = random.choice(unvisited_neighbors_deltas)
165
166                # add connection
167                dim: int = np.argmax(np.abs(delta))
168                # if positive, down/right from current coord
169                # if negative, up/left from current coord (down/right from neighbor)
170                clist_node: Coord = (
171                    current_coord if (delta.sum() > 0) else chosen_neighbor
172                )
173                connection_list[dim, clist_node[0], clist_node[1]] = True
174
175                # add to visited cells and stack
176                visited_cells.add(tuple(chosen_neighbor))
177                stack.append(chosen_neighbor)
178
179                # Update current tree depth
180                current_tree_depth += 1
181            else:
182                current_tree_depth -= 1
183
184        output = LatticeMaze(
185            connection_list=connection_list,
186            generation_meta=dict(
187                func_name="gen_dfs",
188                grid_shape=grid_shape,
189                start_coord=start_coord,
190                n_accessible_cells=int(n_accessible_cells),
191                max_tree_depth=int(max_tree_depth),
192                # oh my god this took so long to track down. its almost 5am and I've spent like 2 hours on this bug
193                # it was checking that len(visited_cells) == n_accessible_cells, but this means that the maze is
194                # treated as fully connected even when it is most certainly not, causing solving the maze to break
195                fully_connected=bool(len(visited_cells) == n_total_cells),
196                visited_cells={tuple(int(x) for x in coord) for coord in visited_cells},
197            ),
198        )
199
200        return output

generate a lattice maze using depth first search, iterative

Arguments

  • grid_shape: Coord: the shape of the grid
  • lattice_dim: int: the dimension of the lattice (default: 2)
  • accessible_cells: int | float |None: the number of accessible cells in the maze. If None, defaults to the total number of cells in the grid. if a float, asserts it is <= 1 and treats it as a proportion of total cells (default: None)
  • max_tree_depth: int | float | None: the maximum depth of the tree. If None, defaults to 2 * accessible_cells. if a float, asserts it is <= 1 and treats it as a proportion of the sum of the grid shape (default: None)
  • do_forks: bool: whether to allow forks in the maze. If False, the maze will be have no forks and will be a simple hallway.
  • start_coord: Coord | None: the starting coordinate of the generation algorithm. If None, defaults to a random coordinate.

algorithm

  1. Choose the initial cell, mark it as visited and push it to the stack
  2. While the stack is not empty
    1. Pop a cell from the stack and make it a current cell
    2. If the current cell has any neighbours which have not been visited
      1. Push the current cell to the stack
      2. Choose one of the unvisited neighbours
      3. Remove the wall between the current cell and the chosen cell
      4. Mark the chosen cell as visited and push it to the stack

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:

723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

class MazeDataset(typing.Generic[+T_co]):
View on GitHub 
224class MazeDataset(GPTDataset):
225    """a maze dataset class. This is a collection of solved mazes, and should be initialized via `MazeDataset.from_config`"""
226
227    def __init__(
228        self,
229        cfg: MazeDatasetConfig,
230        mazes: typing.Sequence[SolvedMaze],
231        generation_metadata_collected: dict | None = None,
232    ) -> None:
233        super().__init__()
234        self.cfg: MazeDatasetConfig = cfg
235        self.mazes: list[SolvedMaze] = list(mazes)
236        self.generation_metadata_collected: dict | None = generation_metadata_collected
237
238    def data_hash(self) -> int:
239        return stable_hash(str(tuple([x.serialize() for x in self.mazes])))
240
241    def __getitem__(self, i: int) -> SolvedMaze:
242        return self.mazes[i]
243
244    def __deepcopy__(self, memo) -> "MazeDataset":
245        return MazeDataset.load(self._serialize_full())
246
247    def as_tokens(
248        self,
249        maze_tokenizer,  # TODO: MazeTokenizer
250        limit: int | None = None,
251        join_tokens_individual_maze: bool = False,
252    ) -> list[list[str]] | list[str]:
253        """return the dataset as tokens according to the passed `maze_tokenizer`
254
255        the `maze_tokenizer` should be either a `MazeTokenizer` or a `ModularMazeTokenizer`
256
257        if `join_tokens_individual_maze` is True, then the tokens of each maze are
258        joined with a space, and the result is a list of strings.
259        i.e.:
260
261            >>> dataset.as_tokens(join_tokens_individual_maze=False)
262            [["a", "b", "c"], ["d", "e", "f"]]
263            >>> dataset.as_tokens(join_tokens_individual_maze=True)
264            ["a b c", "d e f"]
265        """
266        output: list[list[str]] = [
267            maze.as_tokens(maze_tokenizer) for maze in self.mazes[:limit]
268        ]
269        if join_tokens_individual_maze:
270            return [" ".join(tokens) for tokens in output]
271        else:
272            return output
273
274    def __len__(self) -> int:
275        return len(self.mazes)
276
277    def __eq__(self, other: typing.Any) -> bool:
278        if not isinstance(other, MazeDataset):
279            return NotImplemented
280        # TODO: compare hashes of data instead of the data itself?
281        return self.cfg == other.cfg and self.mazes == other.mazes
282
283    @classmethod
284    def generate(
285        cls,
286        cfg: MazeDatasetConfig,
287        gen_parallel: bool = False,
288        pool_kwargs: dict | None = None,
289        verbose: bool = False,
290    ) -> "MazeDataset":
291        """generate a maze dataset given a config and some generation parameters"""
292
293        # avoid copying since we dont want to pickle the staticmethod, just load/serialize it to avoid modifying the original config
294        cfg_cpy = MazeDatasetConfig.load(cfg.serialize())
295
296        if pool_kwargs is None:
297            pool_kwargs = dict()
298        mazes: list[SolvedMaze] = list()
299        maze_indexes: Int[np.int8, "maze_index"] = np.arange(cfg_cpy.n_mazes)
300
301        solved_mazes: list[SolvedMaze]
302        tqdm_kwargs: dict = dict(
303            total=cfg_cpy.n_mazes,
304            unit="maze",
305            desc="generating & solving mazes",
306            disable=not verbose,
307        )
308        # TODO: don't use the global unless generating in parallel!
309        if gen_parallel:
310            with multiprocessing.Pool(
311                **pool_kwargs,
312                initializer=_maze_gen_init_worker,
313                initargs=(cfg_cpy,),
314            ) as pool:
315                solved_mazes = list(
316                    tqdm.tqdm(
317                        pool.imap(
318                            _generate_maze_helper,
319                            maze_indexes,
320                        ),
321                        **tqdm_kwargs,
322                    )
323                )
324        else:
325            _maze_gen_init_worker(cfg_cpy)
326            solved_mazes = list(
327                tqdm.tqdm(
328                    map(
329                        _generate_maze_helper,
330                        maze_indexes,
331                    ),
332                    **tqdm_kwargs,
333                )
334            )
335        # reset seed to default value
336        np.random.seed(cfg_cpy.seed)
337
338        return cls(
339            cfg=cfg_cpy,
340            mazes=solved_mazes,
341        )
342
343    @classmethod
344    def download(cls, cfg: MazeDatasetConfig, **kwargs) -> "MazeDataset":
345        raise NotImplementedError("not implemented yet")
346
347    @classmethod
348    def load(cls, data: JSONitem) -> "MazeDataset":
349        """load from zanj/json"""
350        if data["__format__"] == "MazeDataset:minimal":
351            return cls._load_minimal(data)
352        elif data["__format__"] == "MazeDataset:minimal_soln_cat":
353            return cls._load_minimal_soln_cat(data)
354        elif data["__format__"] == "MazeDataset":
355            if (
356                SERIALIZE_MINIMAL_THRESHOLD == -1
357            ):  # Allow access to `_load_legacy` for profiling
358                return cls._load_legacy(data)
359            return cls._load_full(data)
360        else:
361            raise KeyError(
362                f"`__format__` string {data['__format__']} is not a recognized `MazeDataset` format."
363            )
364
365    @classmethod
366    def _load_full(cls, data: JSONitem) -> "MazeDataset":
367        assert data["__format__"] == "MazeDataset"
368        return cls(
369            cfg=MazeDatasetConfig.load(data["cfg"]),
370            mazes=load_item_recursive(data["mazes"], tuple()),
371            generation_metadata_collected=data["generation_metadata_collected"],
372        )
373
374    @classmethod
375    def _load_minimal(cls, data: JSONitem) -> "MazeDataset":
376        assert data["__format__"] == "MazeDataset:minimal"
377        return cls(
378            cfg=MazeDatasetConfig.load(data["cfg"]),
379            generation_metadata_collected=data["generation_metadata_collected"],
380            mazes=[
381                SolvedMaze(
382                    clist,
383                    soln[:slen, ...],
384                )
385                for clist, slen, soln in zip(
386                    load_item_recursive(data["maze_connection_lists"], tuple()),
387                    load_item_recursive(data["maze_solution_lengths"], tuple()),
388                    load_item_recursive(data["maze_solutions"], tuple()),
389                    # load_item_recursive(data["maze_endpoints"], tuple()),
390                )
391            ],
392        )
393
394    @classmethod
395    def _load_minimal_soln_cat(cls, data: JSONitem) -> "MazeDataset":
396        assert data["__format__"] == "MazeDataset:minimal_soln_cat"
397
398        maze_solution_lengths = load_item_recursive(
399            data["maze_solution_lengths"], tuple()
400        )
401        maze_solutions_concat = load_item_recursive(
402            data["maze_solutions_concat"], tuple()
403        )
404        maze_solutions = np.split(
405            maze_solutions_concat, np.cumsum(maze_solution_lengths)[:-1], axis=0
406        )
407
408        return cls(
409            cfg=load_item_recursive(data["cfg"], tuple()),
410            generation_metadata_collected=load_item_recursive(
411                data["generation_metadata_collected"], tuple()
412            ),
413            mazes=[
414                SolvedMaze(
415                    connection_list=clist,
416                    solution=soln,
417                )
418                for clist, soln in zip(
419                    load_item_recursive(data["maze_connection_lists"], tuple()),
420                    # load_item_recursive(data["maze_endpoints"], tuple()),
421                    maze_solutions,
422                )
423            ],
424        )
425
426    @classmethod
427    def _load_legacy(cls, data: JSONitem) -> "MazeDataset":
428        """Legacy `load` method from <0.5.2. Used exclusively for profiling comparison."""
429        assert data["__format__"] == "MazeDataset"
430        return cls(
431            **{
432                key: load_item_recursive(data[key], tuple())
433                for key in ["cfg", "mazes", "generation_metadata_collected"]
434            }
435        )
436
437    def serialize(self) -> JSONitem:
438        """serialize to zanj/json"""
439        if (
440            SERIALIZE_MINIMAL_THRESHOLD is not None
441            and len(self) >= SERIALIZE_MINIMAL_THRESHOLD
442        ):
443            return self._serialize_minimal()
444        return self._serialize_full()
445
446    def _serialize_full(self) -> JSONitem:
447        return {
448            "__format__": "MazeDataset",
449            "cfg": json_serialize(self.cfg),
450            "mazes": json_serialize(self.mazes),
451            "generation_metadata_collected": json_serialize(
452                self.generation_metadata_collected
453            ),
454        }
455
456    def _serialize_minimal(self) -> JSONitem:
457        "alternate serialization where metadata is collected and mazes are stored in concatenated form"
458        if self.generation_metadata_collected is None:
459            filtered_meta = self.filter_by.collect_generation_meta()
460        else:
461            filtered_meta = self
462
463        max_solution_len: int = max(m.solution.shape[0] for m in filtered_meta.mazes)
464        n_mazes: int = len(filtered_meta.mazes)
465        grid_n: int = filtered_meta.cfg.grid_n
466
467        maze_connection_lists: np.ndarray = np.empty(
468            (n_mazes, 2, grid_n, grid_n), dtype=np.bool_
469        )
470        # maze_endpoints: np.ndarray = np.empty((n_mazes, 2, 2), dtype=np.int8)
471        maze_solution_lengths: np.ndarray = np.empty((n_mazes,), dtype=np.int32)
472        maze_solutions: np.ndarray = np.empty(
473            (n_mazes, max_solution_len, 2), dtype=np.int8
474        )
475
476        for idx, maze in enumerate(filtered_meta.mazes):
477            maze_connection_lists[idx] = maze.connection_list
478            # maze_endpoints[idx] = np.array([maze.start_pos, maze.end_pos])
479            maze_solution_lengths[idx] = maze.solution.shape[0]
480            maze_solutions[idx, : maze.solution.shape[0]] = maze.solution
481
482        return dict(
483            __format__="MazeDataset:minimal",
484            cfg=json_serialize(filtered_meta.cfg),
485            generation_metadata_collected=json_serialize(
486                filtered_meta.generation_metadata_collected
487            ),
488            maze_connection_lists=maze_connection_lists,
489            # maze_endpoints=maze_endpoints,
490            maze_solution_lengths=maze_solution_lengths,
491            maze_solutions=maze_solutions,
492        )
493
494    def _serialize_minimal_soln_cat(self) -> JSONitem:
495        "alternate serialization where metadata is collected, and mazes and their solutions are stored in concatenated form"
496        if self.generation_metadata_collected is None:
497            filtered_meta = self.filter_by.collect_generation_meta()
498        else:
499            filtered_meta = self
500
501        maze_solution_lengths: np.ndarray = np.array(
502            [m.solution.shape[0] for m in filtered_meta.mazes],
503            dtype=np.int32,
504        )
505        n_mazes: int = len(filtered_meta.mazes)
506        grid_n: int = filtered_meta.cfg.grid_n
507        total_solution_len: int = np.sum(maze_solution_lengths)
508
509        maze_connection_lists: np.ndarray = np.empty(
510            (n_mazes, 2, grid_n, grid_n), dtype=np.bool_
511        )
512        maze_endpoints: np.ndarray = np.empty((n_mazes, 2, 2), dtype=np.int8)
513        maze_solutions_concat: np.ndarray = np.empty(
514            (total_solution_len, 2), dtype=np.int8
515        )
516
517        solutions_running_idx: int = 0
518        for idx, maze in enumerate(filtered_meta.mazes):
519            maze_connection_lists[idx] = maze.connection_list
520            maze_endpoints[idx] = np.array([maze.start_pos, maze.end_pos])
521            soln_len: int = maze.solution.shape[0]
522            maze_solution_lengths[idx] = soln_len
523            maze_solutions_concat[
524                solutions_running_idx : solutions_running_idx + soln_len
525            ] = maze.solution
526            solutions_running_idx += soln_len
527
528        return dict(
529            __format__="MazeDataset:minimal_soln_cat",
530            cfg=json_serialize(filtered_meta.cfg),
531            generation_metadata_collected=json_serialize(
532                filtered_meta.generation_metadata_collected
533            ),
534            maze_connection_lists=maze_connection_lists,
535            maze_endpoints=maze_endpoints,
536            maze_solution_lengths=maze_solution_lengths,
537            maze_solutions_concat=maze_solutions_concat,
538        )
539
540    def update_self_config(self):
541        """update the config to match the current state of the dataset (number of mazes, such as after filtering)"""
542        self.cfg.n_mazes = len(self.mazes)
543
544    def custom_maze_filter(
545        self,
546        method: typing.Callable[[SolvedMaze], bool],
547        **kwargs,
548    ) -> "MazeDataset":
549        """filter the dataset using a custom method"""
550        output: MazeDataset = MazeDataset(
551            cfg=copy.deepcopy(self.cfg),
552            mazes=[m for m in self.mazes if method(m, **kwargs)],
553        )
554        output.cfg.applied_filters.append(
555            {
556                "name": f"__custom__:{method.__name__}",
557                "kwargs": kwargs,
558            }
559        )
560        output.update_self_config()
561        return output

class MazeDatasetCollection(typing.Generic[+T_co]):
View on GitHub 
 72class MazeDatasetCollection(GPTDataset):
 73    """a collection of maze datasets"""
 74
 75    def __init__(
 76        self,
 77        cfg: MazeDatasetCollectionConfig,
 78        maze_datasets: list[MazeDataset],
 79        generation_metadata_collected: dict | None = None,
 80    ) -> None:
 81        super().__init__()
 82        self.cfg: MazeDatasetCollectionConfig = cfg
 83        self.maze_datasets: list[MazeDataset] = list(maze_datasets)
 84        for c, ds in zip(self.cfg.maze_dataset_configs, self.maze_datasets):
 85            assert c.name == ds.cfg.name
 86            assert c == ds.cfg
 87
 88        self.generation_metadata_collected: dict | None = generation_metadata_collected
 89
 90    @property
 91    def dataset_lengths(self) -> list[int]:
 92        return [len(dataset) for dataset in self.maze_datasets]
 93
 94    @property
 95    def dataset_cum_lengths(self) -> Int[np.ndarray, "indices"]:
 96        return np.array(list(itertools.accumulate(self.dataset_lengths)))
 97
 98    @cached_property
 99    def mazes(self) -> list[LatticeMaze]:
100        return list(
101            itertools.chain.from_iterable(
102                dataset.mazes for dataset in self.maze_datasets
103            )
104        )
105
106    def __len__(self) -> int:
107        return sum(len(dataset) for dataset in self.maze_datasets)
108
109    def __getitem__(self, index: int):
110        # find which dataset the index belongs to
111        # we add 1, since np.searchsorted returns the
112        # index of the last element that is strictly less than the target
113        # while we want the index of the last element less than or equal to the target
114        dataset_idx: int = np.searchsorted(self.dataset_cum_lengths, index + 1)
115        index_adjusted: int = index
116        if dataset_idx > 0:
117            # if the index is 0, `dataset_idx - 1` will be -1.
118            # We just want to use the base index
119            index_adjusted -= self.dataset_cum_lengths[dataset_idx - 1]
120        return self.maze_datasets[dataset_idx][index_adjusted]
121
122    @classmethod
123    def generate(
124        cls, cfg: MazeDatasetCollectionConfig, **kwargs
125    ) -> "MazeDatasetCollection":
126        datasets = [
127            MazeDataset.generate(config, **kwargs)
128            for config in cfg.maze_dataset_configs
129        ]
130        return cls(cfg, datasets)
131
132    @classmethod
133    def download(
134        cls, cfg: MazeDatasetCollectionConfig, **kwargs
135    ) -> "MazeDatasetCollection":
136        datasets = [
137            MazeDataset.download(config, **kwargs)
138            for config in cfg.maze_dataset_configs
139        ]
140        return cls(cfg, datasets)
141
142    def serialize(self) -> JSONitem:
143        return dict(
144            __format__="MazeDatasetCollection",
145            cfg=self.cfg.serialize(),
146            maze_datasets=[dataset.serialize() for dataset in self.maze_datasets],
147            generation_metadata_collected=json_serialize(
148                self.generation_metadata_collected
149            ),
150        )
151
152    @classmethod
153    def load(cls, data: JSONitem) -> "MazeDatasetCollection":
154        assert data["__format__"] == "MazeDatasetCollection"
155        return cls(
156            **{
157                key: load_item_recursive(data[key], tuple())
158                for key in ["cfg", "maze_datasets", "generation_metadata_collected"]
159            }

def serialize(self) -> dict[str, typing.Any]:
View on GitHub 
660        def serialize(self) -> dict[str, Any]:
661            result: dict[str, Any] = {
662                "__format__": f"{self.__class__.__name__}(SerializableDataclass)"
663            }
664            # for each field in the class
665            for field in dataclasses.fields(self):  # type: ignore[arg-type]
666                # need it to be our special SerializableField
667                if not isinstance(field, SerializableField):
668                    raise NotSerializableFieldException(
669                        f"Field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__} is not a `SerializableField`, "
670                        f"but a {type(field)} "
671                        "this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!"
672                    )
673
674                # try to save it
675                if field.serialize:
676                    try:
677                        # get the val
678                        value = getattr(self, field.name)
679                        # if it is a serializable dataclass, serialize it
680                        if isinstance(value, SerializableDataclass):
681                            value = value.serialize()
682                        # if the value has a serialization function, use that
683                        if hasattr(value, "serialize") and callable(value.serialize):
684                            value = value.serialize()
685                        # if the field has a serialization function, use that
686                        # it would be nice to be able to override a class's `.serialize()`, but that could lead to some inconsistencies!
687                        elif field.serialization_fn:
688                            value = field.serialization_fn(value)
689
690                        # store the value in the result
691                        result[field.name] = value
692                    except Exception as e:
693                        raise FieldSerializationError(
694                            "\n".join(
695                                [
696                                    f"Error serializing field '{field.name}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}",
697                                    f"{field = }",
698                                    f"{value = }",
699                                    f"{self = }",
700                                ]
701                            )
702                        ) from e
703
704            # store each property if we can get it
705            for prop in self._properties_to_serialize:
706                if hasattr(cls, prop):
707                    value = getattr(self, prop)
708                    result[prop] = value
709                else:
710                    raise AttributeError(
711                        f"Cannot serialize property '{prop}' on class {self.__class__.__module__}.{self.__class__.__name__}"
712                        + f"but it is in {self._properties_to_serialize = }"
713                        + f"\n{self = }"
714                    )
715
716            return result

returns the class as a dict, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

@classmethod
def load(cls, data: Union[dict[str, Any], ~T]) -> Type[~T]:
View on GitHub 
723        @classmethod  # type: ignore[misc]
724        def load(cls, data: dict[str, Any] | T) -> Type[T]:
725            # HACK: this is kind of ugly, but it fixes a lot of issues for when we do recursive loading with ZANJ
726            if isinstance(data, cls):
727                return data
728
729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

272    self: SerializableDataclass,

275    """validate the types of all the fields on a `SerializableDataclass`. calls `SerializableDataclass__validate_field_type` for each field"""
276    return all(
277        SerializableDataclass__validate_fields_types__dict(

279        ).values()
280    )

1045    def __post_init__(self) -> None:
1046        # make things numpy arrays (very jank to override frozen dataclass)
1047        self.__dict__["start_pos"] = np.array(self.start_pos)
1048        self.__dict__["end_pos"] = np.array(self.end_pos)
1049        assert self.start_pos is not None
1050        assert self.end_pos is not None
1051        # check that start and end are in bounds
1052        if (
1053            self.start_pos[0] >= self.grid_shape[0]
1054            or self.start_pos[1] >= self.grid_shape[1]
1055        ):
1056            raise ValueError(
1057                f"start_pos {self.start_pos} is out of bounds for grid shape {self.grid_shape}"
1058            )
1059        if (
1060            self.end_pos[0] >= self.grid_shape[0]
1061            or self.end_pos[1] >= self.grid_shape[1]
1062        ):
1063            raise ValueError(

729            assert isinstance(
730                data, typing.Mapping
731            ), f"When loading {cls.__name__ = } expected a Mapping, but got {type(data) = }:\n{data = }"
732
733            cls_type_hints: dict[str, Any] = get_cls_type_hints(cls)
734
735            # initialize dict for keeping what we will pass to the constructor
736            ctor_kwargs: dict[str, Any] = dict()
737
738            # iterate over the fields of the class
739            for field in dataclasses.fields(cls):
740                # check if the field is a SerializableField
741                assert isinstance(
742                    field, SerializableField
743                ), f"Field '{field.name}' on class {cls.__name__} is not a SerializableField, but a {type(field)}. this state should be inaccessible, please report this bug!\nhttps://github.com/mivanit/muutils/issues/new"
744
745                # check if the field is in the data and if it should be initialized
746                if (field.name in data) and field.init:
747                    # get the value, we will be processing it
748                    value: Any = data[field.name]
749
750                    # get the type hint for the field
751                    field_type_hint: Any = cls_type_hints.get(field.name, None)
752
753                    # we rely on the init of `SerializableField` to check that only one of `loading_fn` and `deserialize_fn` is set
754                    if field.deserialize_fn:
755                        # if it has a deserialization function, use that
756                        value = field.deserialize_fn(value)
757                    elif field.loading_fn:
758                        # if it has a loading function, use that
759                        value = field.loading_fn(data)
760                    elif (
761                        field_type_hint is not None
762                        and hasattr(field_type_hint, "load")
763                        and callable(field_type_hint.load)
764                    ):
765                        # if no loading function but has a type hint with a load method, use that
766                        if isinstance(value, dict):
767                            value = field_type_hint.load(value)
768                        else:
769                            raise FieldLoadingError(
770                                f"Cannot load value into {field_type_hint}, expected {type(value) = } to be a dict\n{value = }"
771                            )
772                    else:
773                        # assume no loading needs to happen, keep `value` as-is
774                        pass
775
776                    # store the value in the constructor kwargs
777                    ctor_kwargs[field.name] = value
778
779            # create a new instance of the class with the constructor kwargs
780            output: cls = cls(**ctor_kwargs)
781
782            # validate the types of the fields if needed
783            if on_typecheck_mismatch != ErrorMode.IGNORE:
784                output.validate_fields_types(on_typecheck_error=on_typecheck_error)
785
786            # return the new instance
787            return output

takes in an appropriately structured dict and returns an instance of the class, implemented by using @serializable_dataclass decorator

View on GitHub

274) -> bool:
