224    @staticmethod
225    def gen_wilson(
226        grid_shape: Coord,
227    ) -> LatticeMaze:
228        """Generate a lattice maze using Wilson's algorithm.
229
230        # Algorithm
231        Wilson's algorithm generates an unbiased (random) maze
232        sampled from the uniform distribution over all mazes, using loop-erased random walks. The generated maze is
233        acyclic and all cells are part of a unique connected space.
234        https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maze_generation_algorithm#Wilson's_algorithm
235        """
236
237        # Initialize grid and visited cells
238        connection_list: ConnectionList = np.zeros((2, *grid_shape), dtype=np.bool_)
239        visited: Bool[np.ndarray, "x y"] = np.zeros(grid_shape, dtype=np.bool_)
240
241        # Choose a random cell and mark it as visited
242        start_coord: Coord = _random_start_coord(grid_shape, None)
243        visited[start_coord[0], start_coord[1]] = True
244        del start_coord
245
246        while not visited.all():
247            # Perform loop-erased random walk from another random cell
248
249            # Choose walk_start only from unvisited cells
250            unvisited_coords: CoordArray = np.column_stack(np.where(~visited))
251            walk_start: Coord = unvisited_coords[
252                np.random.choice(unvisited_coords.shape[0])
253            ]
254
255            # Perform the random walk
256            path: list[Coord] = [walk_start]
257            current: Coord = walk_start
258
259            # exit the loop once the current path hits a visited cell
260            while not visited[current[0], current[1]]:
261                # find a valid neighbor (one always exists on a lattice)
262                neighbors: CoordArray = get_neighbors_in_bounds(current, grid_shape)
263                next_cell: Coord = neighbors[np.random.choice(neighbors.shape[0])]
264
265                # Check for loop
266                loop_exit: int | None = None
267                for i, p in enumerate(path):
268                    if np.array_equal(next_cell, p):
269                        loop_exit = i
270                        break
271
272                # erase the loop, or continue the walk
273                if loop_exit is not None:
274                    # this removes everything after and including the loop start
275                    path = path[: loop_exit + 1]
276                    # reset current cell to end of path
277                    current = path[-1]
278                else:
279                    path.append(next_cell)
280                    current = next_cell
281
282            # Add the path to the maze
283            for i in range(len(path) - 1):
284                c_1: Coord = path[i]
285                c_2: Coord = path[i + 1]
286
287                # find the dimension of the connection
288                delta: Coord = c_2 - c_1
289                dim: int = np.argmax(np.abs(delta))
290
291                # if positive, down/right from current coord
292                # if negative, up/left from current coord (down/right from neighbor)
293                clist_node: Coord = c_1 if (delta.sum() > 0) else c_2
294                connection_list[dim, clist_node[0], clist_node[1]] = True
295                visited[c_1[0], c_1[1]] = True
296                # we dont add c_2 because the last c_2 will have already been visited
297
298        return LatticeMaze(
299            connection_list=connection_list,
300            generation_meta=dict(
301                func_name="gen_wilson",
302                grid_shape=grid_shape,
303                fully_connected=True,
304            ),
305        )
306
307    @staticmethod
308    def gen_percolation(
309        grid_shape: Coord,
310        p: float = 0.4,
311        lattice_dim: int = 2,
312        start_coord: Coord | None = None,
313    ) -> LatticeMaze:
314        """generate a lattice maze using simple percolation
315
316        note that p in the range (0.4, 0.7) gives the most interesting mazes
317
318        # Arguments
319        - `grid_shape: Coord`: the shape of the grid
320        - `lattice_dim: int`: the dimension of the lattice (default: `2`)
321        - `p: float`: the probability of a cell being accessible (default: `0.5`)
322        - `start_coord: Coord | None`: the starting coordinate for the connected component (default: `None` will give a random start)
323        """
324        assert p >= 0 and p <= 1, f"p must be between 0 and 1, got {p}"
325        grid_shape: Coord = np.array(grid_shape)
326
327        start_coord = _random_start_coord(grid_shape, start_coord)
328
329        connection_list: ConnectionList = np.random.rand(lattice_dim, *grid_shape) < p
330
331        connection_list = _fill_edges_with_walls(connection_list)
332
333        output: LatticeMaze = LatticeMaze(
334            connection_list=connection_list,
335            generation_meta=dict(
336                func_name="gen_percolation",
337                grid_shape=grid_shape,
338                percolation_p=p,
339                start_coord=start_coord,
340            ),
341        )
342
343        output.generation_meta["visited_cells"] = output.gen_connected_component_from(
344            start_coord
345        )
346
347        return output
348
349    @staticmethod
350    def gen_dfs_percolation(
351        grid_shape: Coord,
352        p: float = 0.4,
353        lattice_dim: int = 2,
354        accessible_cells: int | None = None,
355        max_tree_depth: int | None = None,
356        start_coord: Coord | None = None,
357    ) -> LatticeMaze:
358        """dfs and then percolation (adds cycles)"""
359        grid_shape: Coord = np.array(grid_shape)
360        start_coord = _random_start_coord(grid_shape, start_coord)
361
362        # generate initial maze via dfs
363        maze: LatticeMaze = LatticeMazeGenerators.gen_dfs(
364            grid_shape=grid_shape,
365            lattice_dim=lattice_dim,
366            accessible_cells=accessible_cells,
367            max_tree_depth=max_tree_depth,
368            start_coord=start_coord,
369        )
370
371        # percolate
372        connection_list_perc: np.ndarray = (
373            np.random.rand(*maze.connection_list.shape) < p
374        )
375        connection_list_perc = _fill_edges_with_walls(connection_list_perc)
376
377        maze.__dict__["connection_list"] = np.logical_or(
378            maze.connection_list, connection_list_perc
379        )
380
381        maze.generation_meta["func_name"] = "gen_dfs_percolation"
382        maze.generation_meta["percolation_p"] = p
383        maze.generation_meta["visited_cells"] = maze.gen_connected_component_from(
384            start_coord
385        )
386
387        return maze

generate a lattice maze using depth first search, iterative

Arguments

  • grid_shape: Coord: the shape of the grid
  • lattice_dim: int: the dimension of the lattice (default: 2)
  • accessible_cells: int | float |None: the number of accessible cells in the maze. If None, defaults to the total number of cells in the grid. if a float, asserts it is <= 1 and treats it as a proportion of total cells (default: None)
  • max_tree_depth: int | float | None: the maximum depth of the tree. If None, defaults to 2 * accessible_cells. if a float, asserts it is <= 1 and treats it as a proportion of the sum of the grid shape (default: None)
  • do_forks: bool: whether to allow forks in the maze. If False, the maze will be have no forks and will be a simple hallway.
  • start_coord: Coord | None: the starting coordinate of the generation algorithm. If None, defaults to a random coordinate.

algorithm

  1. Choose the initial cell, mark it as visited and push it to the stack
  2. While the stack is not empty
    1. Pop a cell from the stack and make it a current cell
    2. If the current cell has any neighbours which have not been visited
      1. Push the current cell to the stack
      2. Choose one of the unvisited neighbours
      3. Remove the wall between the current cell and the chosen cell
      4. Mark the chosen cell as visited and push it to the stack
@staticmethod
def gen_prim( grid_shape: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'], lattice_dim: int = 2, accessible_cells: int | float | None = None, max_tree_depth: int | float | None = None, do_forks: bool = True, start_coord: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'] | None = None) -> LatticeMaze:
View on GitHub

212            "gen_prim does not correctly implement prim's algorithm, see issue: https://github.com/understanding-search/maze-dataset/issues/12",
213        )
214        return LatticeMazeGenerators.gen_dfs(

217            accessible_cells=accessible_cells,
218            max_tree_depth=max_tree_depth,

221            randomized_stack=True,
222        )
@staticmethod
def gen_wilson( grid_shape: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col']) -> LatticeMaze:
View on GitHub 
224    @staticmethod
225    def gen_wilson(
226        grid_shape: Coord,
227    ) -> LatticeMaze:
228        """Generate a lattice maze using Wilson's algorithm.
229
230        # Algorithm
231        Wilson's algorithm generates an unbiased (random) maze
232        sampled from the uniform distribution over all mazes, using loop-erased random walks. The generated maze is
233        acyclic and all cells are part of a unique connected space.
234        https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maze_generation_algorithm#Wilson's_algorithm
235        """
236
237        # Initialize grid and visited cells
238        connection_list: ConnectionList = np.zeros((2, *grid_shape), dtype=np.bool_)
239        visited: Bool[np.ndarray, "x y"] = np.zeros(grid_shape, dtype=np.bool_)
240
241        # Choose a random cell and mark it as visited
242        start_coord: Coord = _random_start_coord(grid_shape, None)
243        visited[start_coord[0], start_coord[1]] = True
244        del start_coord
245
246        while not visited.all():
247            # Perform loop-erased random walk from another random cell
248
249            # Choose walk_start only from unvisited cells
250            unvisited_coords: CoordArray = np.column_stack(np.where(~visited))
251            walk_start: Coord = unvisited_coords[
252                np.random.choice(unvisited_coords.shape[0])
253            ]
254
255            # Perform the random walk
256            path: list[Coord] = [walk_start]
257            current: Coord = walk_start
258
259            # exit the loop once the current path hits a visited cell
260            while not visited[current[0], current[1]]:
261                # find a valid neighbor (one always exists on a lattice)
262                neighbors: CoordArray = get_neighbors_in_bounds(current, grid_shape)
263                next_cell: Coord = neighbors[np.random.choice(neighbors.shape[0])]
264
265                # Check for loop
266                loop_exit: int | None = None
267                for i, p in enumerate(path):
268                    if np.array_equal(next_cell, p):
269                        loop_exit = i
270                        break
271
272                # erase the loop, or continue the walk
273                if loop_exit is not None:
274                    # this removes everything after and including the loop start
275                    path = path[: loop_exit + 1]
276                    # reset current cell to end of path
277                    current = path[-1]
278                else:
279                    path.append(next_cell)
280                    current = next_cell
281
282            # Add the path to the maze
283            for i in range(len(path) - 1):
284                c_1: Coord = path[i]
285                c_2: Coord = path[i + 1]
286
287                # find the dimension of the connection
288                delta: Coord = c_2 - c_1
289                dim: int = np.argmax(np.abs(delta))
290
291                # if positive, down/right from current coord
292                # if negative, up/left from current coord (down/right from neighbor)
293                clist_node: Coord = c_1 if (delta.sum() > 0) else c_2
294                connection_list[dim, clist_node[0], clist_node[1]] = True
295                visited[c_1[0], c_1[1]] = True
296                # we dont add c_2 because the last c_2 will have already been visited
297
298        return LatticeMaze(
299            connection_list=connection_list,
300            generation_meta=dict(
301                func_name="gen_wilson",
302                grid_shape=grid_shape,
303                fully_connected=True,
304            ),
305        )

Generate a lattice maze using Wilson's algorithm.

Algorithm

Wilson's algorithm generates an unbiased (random) maze sampled from the uniform distribution over all mazes, using loop-erased random walks. The generated maze is acyclic and all cells are part of a unique connected space. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maze_generation_algorithm#Wilson's_algorithm

@staticmethod
def gen_percolation( grid_shape: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'], p: float = 0.4, lattice_dim: int = 2, start_coord: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'] | None = None) -> LatticeMaze:
View on GitHub 
307    @staticmethod
308    def gen_percolation(
309        grid_shape: Coord,
310        p: float = 0.4,
311        lattice_dim: int = 2,
312        start_coord: Coord | None = None,
313    ) -> LatticeMaze:
314        """generate a lattice maze using simple percolation
315
316        note that p in the range (0.4, 0.7) gives the most interesting mazes
317
318        # Arguments
319        - `grid_shape: Coord`: the shape of the grid
320        - `lattice_dim: int`: the dimension of the lattice (default: `2`)
321        - `p: float`: the probability of a cell being accessible (default: `0.5`)
322        - `start_coord: Coord | None`: the starting coordinate for the connected component (default: `None` will give a random start)
323        """
324        assert p >= 0 and p <= 1, f"p must be between 0 and 1, got {p}"
325        grid_shape: Coord = np.array(grid_shape)
326
327        start_coord = _random_start_coord(grid_shape, start_coord)
328
329        connection_list: ConnectionList = np.random.rand(lattice_dim, *grid_shape) < p
330
331        connection_list = _fill_edges_with_walls(connection_list)
332
333        output: LatticeMaze = LatticeMaze(
334            connection_list=connection_list,
335            generation_meta=dict(
336                func_name="gen_percolation",
337                grid_shape=grid_shape,
338                percolation_p=p,
339                start_coord=start_coord,
340            ),
341        )
342
343        output.generation_meta["visited_cells"] = output.gen_connected_component_from(
344            start_coord
345        )
346
347        return output

generate a lattice maze using simple percolation

note that p in the range (0.4, 0.7) gives the most interesting mazes

Arguments

  • grid_shape: Coord: the shape of the grid
  • lattice_dim: int: the dimension of the lattice (default: 2)
  • p: float: the probability of a cell being accessible (default: 0.5)
  • start_coord: Coord | None: the starting coordinate for the connected component (default: None will give a random start)
@staticmethod
def gen_dfs_percolation( grid_shape: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'], p: float = 0.4, lattice_dim: int = 2, accessible_cells: int | None = None, max_tree_depth: int | None = None, start_coord: jaxtyping.Int8[ndarray, 'row_col'] | None = None) -> LatticeMaze:
View on GitHub 
349    @staticmethod
350    def gen_dfs_percolation(
351        grid_shape: Coord,
352        p: float = 0.4,
353        lattice_dim: int = 2,
354        accessible_cells: int | None = None,
355        max_tree_depth: int | None = None,
356        start_coord: Coord | None = None,
357    ) -> LatticeMaze:
358        """dfs and then percolation (adds cycles)"""
359        grid_shape: Coord = np.array(grid_shape)
360        start_coord = _random_start_coord(grid_shape, start_coord)
361
362        # generate initial maze via dfs
363        maze: LatticeMaze = LatticeMazeGenerators.gen_dfs(
364            grid_shape=grid_shape,
365            lattice_dim=lattice_dim,
366            accessible_cells=accessible_cells,
367            max_tree_depth=max_tree_depth,
368            start_coord=start_coord,
369        )
370
371        # percolate
372        connection_list_perc: np.ndarray = (
373            np.random.rand(*maze.connection_list.shape) < p
374        )
375        connection_list_perc = _fill_edges_with_walls(connection_list_perc)
376
377        maze.__dict__["connection_list"] = np.logical_or(
378            maze.connection_list, connection_list_perc
379        )
380
381        maze.generation_meta["func_name"] = "gen_dfs_percolation"
382        maze.generation_meta["percolation_p"] = p
383        maze.generation_meta["visited_cells"] = maze.gen_connected_component_from(
384            start_coord
385        )
386
387        return maze
